<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;Police recently dubbed British paedophile, Douglas Lindsell the 'most prolific sex predator' on the internet. Lindsell, 64, was jailed for 5 years in October when police raided his home and found the names and profiles of 73 girls, some as young as 12 years old, on his PC.<br>
Lindsell had pretended to be a young boy in chat room conversations and sent an old picture of his son, which he claimed was him, to the girls he targeted. After he had gained their confidence and the contact details he required, he would then harass the victims via e-mail and telephone - he even met with some.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
this is the bit of the article that made me go hmm though:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;A majority of Lindsell's 'Grooming' (where paedophiles gathers children’s contact details via deception) happened in Microsoft’s MSN chat rooms - so it was no surprise when Microsoft closed down its 10,000+ chat rooms...&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Now... this is what niggles me a lot, after reading more articles on this it appears a lot of you praise Microsoft for this &quot;swift&quot; decision which is &quot;protecting our children” but I cant help but wonder if its anything to do with the financial burden they would face.<br>
It's fair to say that maintaining MSN free chat rooms returned NO substantial gains. It’s also true that Microsoft would find it almost impossible to continue to provide un-monitored chat rooms following this Lindsell case... so the way I see it they were left with two options... pay for moderation of these chat rooms or close them all together.<br>
<br>
Most critics of Microsoft are really annoyed with they way they spun it too, advertising it as &quot;MSN takes action on chat&quot; (read the press release they sent out on day the day of its closure) - it went on to state that the decision was being taken as part of a &quot;global effort to provide consumers with safer, more secure and positive online experiences. These changes will help protect MSN users from SPAM and inappropriate communication.&quot; At no point has anyone from MSN said &quot;Paying for moderators is out of the question so were just going to close all the rooms&quot;.<br>
<br>
Statistics show today that, of the one in five children who have regularly used chat rooms, more than half have engaged in sex chat so there is no doubt in my mind that children’s chat rooms should be moderated (if not all chat rooms).... so is Microsoft’s move a responsible one? Microsoft may have covered its back but doesn’t this kind of decision just force children to find different more seedy chat rooms where they will continue to be targeted - with more ease I should imagine.<br>
<br>
With a 7year old brother who often chats online, this worries me a lot, and I was wondering everybody else’s position on this.<br>
