<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Microsoft also needs to ensure that its service is relatively safe<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I'm sure they do. I'm sure they put in place all the appropriate procedures and safeguards to protect their customers' computers from getting viruses, from IP traces and DoS attacks, from release of sensitive real-life information. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>That</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is Microsoft's responsibility, if anything. I'm Microsoft <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>does</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> have a disclaimer in place, and I'm sure it requires chat room users to accept, amongst other rules, that users may not conduct illegal or improper practises via the chatrooms, and that minors must have the consent or supervision of a parent or guardian. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>That</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is MS doing their part. The chatrooms are offered &quot;as-is&quot; - as a medium for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>unmoderated</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> chat. If MS customers choose to abuse the regulations that MS put in place - by 'grooming' small children or, in the case of parents/guardians, by allowing the minor in their care to use the chatroom unsupervised - then MS cannot be held responsible.<br>
